"""
mkt-context | Numbers | chapters 1–2
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-numbers-1-2-fill.py

Ch 1: The military census of Israel at Sinai — ANE parallels in Egyptian and Mesopotamian
      military musters; the 'eleph debate (literal 1,000s vs. clan/unit interpretation);
      Levitical exemption from military census; the administrative formula tradition.
Ch 2: The camp arrangement — four-sided encampment around the Tabernacle with Levitical
      buffer zone; parallels to Egyptian military camp layouts (Kadesh relief); directional
      symbolism (Judah/sunrise); total population logistics.

Note: ch 1 v1 already present (book intro); only vv.2-54 written here.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "2": "<p>The census command — 'Take a census of the entire congregation of Israel by their clans and ancestral houses, counting every male by name' — follows a military-muster format attested across the ancient world. Egyptian papyri from the New Kingdom period (roughly contemporary with the Exodus-era) document military registers listing soldiers by name, unit, and tribal affiliation. The Mesopotamian Mari archives (18th century BCE) contain administrative lists of tribal warrior-leaders with counts very similar in structure to the Numbers census formula. The census is explicitly a military count: the enumerated men are those 'able to serve in the army' (v3). The phrase 'by their clans and ancestral houses' (<em>lemishpechotam lebet avotam</em>) reflects a kinship-based military organization common throughout the Levant in the Late Bronze Age.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The military age threshold of 20 years old is consistent with ancient military practice. Egyptian and Mesopotamian military service generally began in the late teens or early twenties. The phrase 'able to serve in the army' (<em>kol yotse tsava'</em>, literally 'all who go out to the army/host') uses <em>tsava'</em> — both the military army and the organized corps of Levitical workers (same word in v3 for army and in v4:23 for Levitical service). The age of 20 is also the age of full adult accountability in the Torah (Exod 30:14, Lev 27:3-5). Moses and Aaron are commanded to conduct the census together — the civil and priestly leadership jointly oversee the military register.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The appointment of one tribal representative to assist Moses and Aaron — 'each the head of his ancestral house' — establishes a decentralized administrative structure. This parallels the Mesopotamian system of tribal representatives in Mari texts where a designated <em>sugāgum</em> (tribal chief/administrator) handled census and levy matters for each tribal unit. The choice of existing hereditary leaders (rather than appointed officials) reflects the kinship-based social organization of a tribal confederation — each tribe's own elite maintain control over their enrollment data.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The tribal leaders listed in vv.5-15 are the same men who later bring the dedication offerings in ch.7, lead the tribal divisions in ch.2, and are named in ch.10. The consistency across multiple chapters suggests these are not literary constructions but part of a coherent administrative document that the compiler of Numbers preserves intact. From Reuben: Elizur son of Shedeur — the names in the list represent a naming tradition common in the Late Bronze Age Levant where theophoric names (names containing divine elements like <em>El</em>, <em>YHWH</em>, <em>Shaddai</em>) predominate.</p>",
    "6": "<p>From Simeon: Shelumiel son of Zurishaddai. The name <em>Zurishaddai</em> (My Rock is the Almighty, from <em>tsur</em> = rock and <em>Shaddai</em> = Almighty) belongs to the patriarchal naming tradition that uses <em>El Shaddai</em> — the divine name most prominent in Genesis (Gen 17:1; 28:3; 49:25). This naming pattern suggests these tribal leaders preserve ancient theophoric name traditions predating the Mosaic revelation of the divine name YHWH.</p>",
    "7": "<p>From Judah: Nahshon son of Amminadab. Nahshon's placement at the head of the eastern (first marching) division reflects Judah's pre-eminent position in the tribal order — a status rooted in the Abrahamic/Jacobean blessing tradition (Gen 49:8-12). His genealogical prominence is confirmed in Ruth 4:20 and 1 Chr 2:10-11, where he appears as David's ancestor, and in Matt 1:4 as an ancestor of Jesus. The leader of the first tribe is thus implicitly connected to the eventual Davidic-Messianic line.</p>",
    "8": "<p>From Issachar: Nethanel son of Zuar. <em>Nethanel</em> (God has given) is a common theophoric name type throughout the ancient Levant. The tribe of Issachar was associated with the fertile Jezreel Valley region. In the later period, Issachar's men were 'those who had understanding of the times' (1 Chr 12:32), perhaps reflecting a scholarly or calendar-calculating tradition within the tribe.</p>",
    "9": "<p>From Zebulun: Eliab son of Helon. Zebulun's territory bordered the Mediterranean Sea and the Jezreel Valley. The proximity of Zebulun and Issachar in both the tribal list and the marching order reflects their geographic and sibling relationship (both are sons of Leah, Gen 30:18-20).</p>",
    "10": "<p>From the Joseph tribes: Ephraim's leader is Elishama son of Ammihud; Manasseh's is Gamaliel son of Pedahzur. The Joseph tribes are listed together as descendants of Joseph even though counted separately — a reflection of the double portion (Gen 48:22) that split Joseph's inheritance into two half-tribes. The name Gamaliel (<em>God has rewarded</em>) later becomes the name of Saul's teacher (Acts 22:3), the famous rabbinic sage.</p>",
    "11": "<p>From Benjamin: Abidan son of Gideoni. Benjamin, the youngest of Jacob's sons and Rachel's second child, receives tribal parity in the census. The later tribal territory of Benjamin would include Jerusalem. The name <em>Gideoni</em> is related to <em>Gideon</em> (tree-cutter), the later judge whose name may reflect Benjaminite naming traditions.</p>",
    "12": "<p>From Dan: Ahiezer son of Ammishaddai. Dan, the tribe associated with the northern extremity of Israel's territory ('from Dan to Beersheba'), leads the rear guard of the march (2:31). The large census count for Dan (62,700) makes it one of the most numerous tribes. Archaeologically, the site of Tel Dan in northern Israel preserves evidence of Danite settlement and a sanctuary tradition.</p>",
    "13": "<p>From Asher: Pagiel son of Ochran. Asher's territory ran along the Phoenician coast — the most commercially advantageous tribal holding, consistent with Jacob's blessing: 'his food shall be rich, and he shall yield royal delicacies' (Gen 49:20). The Phoenician coast was the source of luxury goods, purple dye, and timber throughout the ancient world.</p>",
    "14": "<p>From Gad: Eliasaph son of Deuel. Gad's territory was east of the Jordan in the Gilead region. The Gadites later negotiate to remain in Transjordan (Num 32), and their military prowess is celebrated in 1 Chr 12:8-15. The tribal name Gad means 'fortune/good luck' (Gen 30:11).</p>",
    "15": "<p>From Naphtali: Ahira son of Enan. Naphtali's territory bordered the Sea of Galilee — the region where the prophet Isaiah foresaw a great light (Isa 9:1-2) that Matthew identifies as the beginning of Jesus's Galilean ministry (Matt 4:15-16). The list of twelve tribal leaders is now complete.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The summary describes these men as <em>qerui'e ha'edah</em> (called ones of the congregation, the designated leaders) — the same term used for the assembly of leaders throughout Numbers. The phrase 'heads of the clans of Israel' uses <em>rashei alfei Yisra'el</em> (heads of the thousands of Israel) where <em>elef</em> (thousand/clan) is the contested term at the heart of the census-number debate. If <em>elef</em> here means 'clan/unit' rather than literally 1,000, these are 'heads of the clan-units of Israel' — a reading that would significantly affect the total enrollment numbers.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Moses and Aaron take the designated men — note the formula <em>vayiqach Mosheh ve'Aharon et ha'anashim ha'eleh asher niqqevu beshemot</em> (who were designated by name) — the census is a formal bureaucratic act, not informal counting. The name-by-name enumeration is the form of an official administrative roll, comparable to Egyptian <em>imy-r</em> (overseer) registers that list personnel by name and unit.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The assembly on the first day of the second month provides an exact chronological anchor: the tabernacle was erected on the first day of the first month of the second year (Exod 40:17); the census begins exactly one month later. The formula 'the people declared their ancestry' (<em>vayityaledu al mishpechotam lebet avotam</em>, they registered themselves according to their genealogical lineage) reflects the importance of genealogical documentation in ancient administrative contexts. Egyptian and Mesopotamian administrative texts show similar formal self-declaration processes for census and military enrollment.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The obedience formula — 'Just as the LORD had commanded Moses, so he counted them in the wilderness of Sinai' — is standard in Numbers for confirming compliance with divine commands. The wilderness of Sinai setting (in the vicinity of the current camp at the base of the mountain) provides the spatial context for the whole chapter.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The census enrollment formula for Reuben follows a consistent pattern for all 12 tribes: 'The descendants of [tribe], recorded by their families and ancestral houses, every male twenty years and older who was able to serve in the army' — followed by the count. Reuben is named first as 'Israel's firstborn' (<em>bekhor Yisra'el</em>), an honorific preserved even though Reuben lost the firstborn blessing (Gen 49:3-4). The preservation of the firstborn title alongside Judah's military precedence reflects the tension between natural birth order and the redirection of covenant blessing that characterizes the patriarchal narratives.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Reuben: 46,500. Each tribal number is given with a precision that suggests an actual census document rather than round-number approximation. The numbers are precise to the hundreds (not rounded to the thousands), which is a characteristic of genuine administrative records. The question of whether these are literal individual counts or unit-based figures (with <em>elef</em> representing a military unit rather than exactly 1,000 men) has been debated since George Mendenhall's 1958 article suggesting that the totals represent a much smaller force of fighting men.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The census formula for Simeon is identical to Reuben's — 'recorded by their families and ancestral houses, every male twenty years and older who was able to serve.' The repetition of the identical formula twelve times creates a cadence of thorough, bureaucratic completeness — a deliberate literary signal that every tribe has been equally processed through the same administrative procedure.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Simeon: 59,300. By the second census in ch.26, Simeon's count has dropped dramatically to 22,200 — a decrease of 37,100 (the largest proportional decline of any tribe). The Talmudic tradition connects this decline to the Baal Peor incident (ch.25), where the offender is identified as a Simeonite prince (25:14). Simeon's later absorption into Judah's territory (Josh 19:1-9) is consistent with a depleted tribal population.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Gad's census formula follows the standard pattern. Gad appears third in the census (after Reuben and Simeon) rather than in the birth-order position (seventh son of Jacob). The tribe's placement in the south division alongside Reuben (ch.2) may reflect a geographic proximity that predates the formal tribal arrangements.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Gad: 45,650 — the only tribal number not a round multiple of 100, giving 45,650 instead of 45,600 or 45,700. This arithmetically irregular number is often cited as evidence of genuine census data rather than symbolic numbers, since symbolic or fabricated totals typically use round figures.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Judah's census formula. Judah is the fourth tribe counted despite being the dominant tribe and leading the eastern march. The birth-order position (fourth son of Leah) determines the census list order, while the marching/camping order in ch.2 reflects military precedence. This distinction between genealogical and military ordering is a bureaucratic sophistication.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Judah: 74,600 — the largest of the twelve tribes' initial count, consistent with Judah's dominant role in the later monarchy and the Davidic covenant. The largest census count going to the tribe from which David and ultimately the Messiah will come is noted in both Jewish and Christian tradition as providentially fitting.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Issachar's census formula. Issachar and Zebulun (vv.28-31) are consistently paired in tribal lists — they are the two youngest sons of Leah (Gen 30:17-20) and their territories were adjacent in the Jezreel Valley and coastal plain. The agricultural fertility of their region may account for the relatively large populations.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Issachar: 54,400.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Zebulun's census formula. Zebulun's territory eventually included the region around Nazareth, making it the tribal homeland of Jesus's upbringing — though the NT describes this primarily in terms of Naphtali and Zebulun together (Matt 4:15 citing Isa 9:1).</p>",
    "31": "<p>Zebulun: 57,400.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Ephraim and Manasseh are both counted as 'descendants of Joseph' — the formula explicitly maintains Joseph's identity even as his sons are treated as independent tribes. This creates 13 tribal units enumerated (12 sons of Jacob minus Levi, plus Ephraim and Manasseh for Joseph), but the count is maintained at 12 by excluding Levi. The dual listing of Joseph's sons fulfills Jacob's blessing in Gen 48:5-6 that Ephraim and Manasseh 'shall be mine as Reuben and Simeon are mine.'</p>",
    "33": "<p>Ephraim: 40,500. By the second census (ch.26), Ephraim has declined to 32,500 while Manasseh has grown to 52,700 — a complete reversal of the birth-order blessing Jacob gave (Gen 48:19-20 where the younger/Ephraim receives the greater blessing). The historical trajectories of the two Joseph tribes reflect the variability of census populations that genuine demographic data would show.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Manasseh's census formula. The Joseph tribes' ordering (Ephraim first, Manasseh second) reflects Jacob's crossing of his hands to give the greater blessing to Ephraim, the younger (Gen 48:14). This reversal is preserved in the census and camping orders consistently throughout Numbers.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Manasseh: 32,200 — the smallest count of all twelve tribes. Later, Manasseh grows to become one of the larger tribes (52,700 in ch.26), reflecting the historical emergence of the Manassite hill-country settlements in the central highlands as a dominant demographic force in pre-monarchic Israel.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Benjamin's census formula. Benjamin was the youngest of Jacob's twelve sons and Rachel's second. The tribe's small but significant territory included Jerusalem, which was on the border between Benjamin and Judah. The Benjaminite kings Saul and Ishbosheth precede the permanent Davidic dynasty.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Benjamin: 35,400.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Dan's census formula. Dan was the first son of Bilhah and the tribe associated with the far northern territory. The Danite migration to the north (Judg 17-18) from their original territory near the Philistine coast is one of the best-documented tribal relocations in the biblical period, with archaeological support at Tel Dan.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Dan: 62,700 — a large count for the son of a concubine. The strength of Dan at this point in the wilderness period contrasts with the tribe's later history of religious apostasy (Judg 18:30-31; 1 Kings 12:29). Dan is notably absent from the 144,000 in Rev 7, replaced by Manasseh.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Asher's census formula. Asher's coastal location on the Phoenician border meant the tribe had access to the most lucrative trade routes of the eastern Mediterranean. The wealth implied by Jacob's blessing ('his food shall be rich, and he shall yield royal delicacies,' Gen 49:20) is consistent with the tribe's advantageous geography.</p>",
    "41": "<p>Asher: 41,500.</p>",
    "42": "<p>Naphtali's census formula. The notation that Naphtali's count covers 'throughout their generations' (<em>toledotam</em>) adds a generational dimension not specified for most other tribes — possibly reflecting a distinctive record-keeping tradition within the tribe, or a textual variant.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Naphtali: 53,400.</p>",
    "44": "<p>The summary statement names Moses, Aaron, and the twelve tribal leaders as the conducting officers of the census — explicitly preserving the names of the co-administrators of the enrollment. The formulaic structure 'one man per ancestral house' reaffirms the decentralized, tribe-by-tribe methodology. The official character of the census is underscored by naming the administrative chain of command.</p>",
    "45": "<p>The summary formula for the enrolled: 'All the Israelites twenty years and older who were able to serve in the army, enrolled by their ancestral houses.' The military character of the census is restated — this is a war register, not a general population census. Ancient Near Eastern military censuses similarly focused on the adult male fighting population: Egyptian records from the New Kingdom (Papyrus Anastasi) and Assyrian annals both record military manpower assessments distinct from general population counts.</p>",
    "46": "<p>The grand total: 603,550 enrolled adult males. This figure has generated extensive scholarly debate. At face value it implies a total population (including women, children, and the uncounted Levites) of 2-2.5 million people — a population too large for the Sinai Peninsula to support logistically and larger than most estimates for the entire population of Egypt at this period. Alternative interpretations include: (1) Literal reading — the miraculous nature of the wilderness provision is precisely the point; (2) Mendenhall/Humphreys theory — <em>elef</em> means 'military unit' not '1,000,' giving a much smaller army of roughly 5,500-6,000 men; (3) Symbolic reading — the numbers encode theological significance (some note 603,550 in Hebrew numerology, or connections to the number of letters in the Torah). No consensus exists, but the text presents the figure as a genuine census result.</p>",
    "47": "<p>The Levitical exemption from the military census is stated without precedent in the ANE — no other ancient culture exempted its religious personnel from military muster. The reasoning given (vv.50-53) is specifically that the Levites are assigned to the tabernacle service rather than military service. The principle of a dedicated non-military religious caste parallels later Brahmin and Buddhist monastic exemptions from military service in other ancient cultures, but in Israel it appears explicitly in the earliest organization of the cult.</p>",
    "48": "<p>The divine command to exclude Levi is a direct prohibition from YHWH, not a Mosaic discretionary decision. The explicit divine instruction ensures that the Levitical exemption is theological, not administrative — it is not a practical concession but a fundamental distinction in the ordering of Israel's society between those who serve YHWH at the sanctuary and those who serve as warriors.</p>",
    "49": "<p>'Do not count the tribe of Levi or include them in the census of the Israelites.' The double exclusion — not counted AND not included in the sum — ensures the Levites are entirely outside the military register. Their separate enumeration will come in ch.3 by a different methodology (from one month old, not twenty years old) and for a different purpose (substitution for the firstborn, not military service).</p>",
    "50": "<p>The positive charge for the Levites — 'appoint them over the tabernacle of the testimony, over all its furnishings, and all that belongs to it' — defines their role as the tabernacle's caretakers and transport corps. The word <em>'edut</em> (testimony/covenant document) in 'tabernacle of the testimony' refers specifically to the ark of the covenant containing the stone tablets — the divine testimony that is the covenant's physical token.</p>",
    "51": "<p>The death penalty for unauthorized approach to the tabernacle — 'any outsider who comes near shall be put to death (<em>yumat</em>)' — establishes the exclusive Levitical access to the sanctuary area. This holy-space restriction is paralleled in Mesopotamian temple regulations (neo-Babylonian temple records specify which personnel classes may enter which temple zones) and Egyptian temple prescriptions (the inner sanctuary accessible only to priests). The difference is that in Israel the restriction is enforced by the Levites on behalf of the entire congregation, not by temple guards on behalf of the king.</p>",
    "52": "<p>The camp organization by tribal standards (<em>degalo</em>, his standard; <em>be'otot</em>, under ensigns) establishes a military formation for the entire camp. The word <em>degel</em> (standard/banner) is related to Akkadian <em>dagālu</em> (to look at, to observe) — the standard is the visual marker used for unit identification in battle. Egyptian military reliefs (Medinet Habu, Karnak) consistently show armies organized under unit standards, and Assyrian reliefs depict similar arrangements. The Israelite tribal standard system fits this broader ANE pattern of military camp organization.</p>",
    "53": "<p>The Levites camp around the tabernacle 'so that wrath does not fall on the congregation of Israel.' The Levitical encirclement serves as a buffer between the holy and the common — a graduated access structure found throughout ancient temple architecture. Mesopotamian temple complexes (e.g., Esagila in Babylon, the Ur III ziggurat complexes) had multiple concentric zones with progressively restricted access. The Levitical encampment creates a living perimeter of sacred personnel that separates the congregation from the divine presence in the tabernacle.</p>",
    "54": "<p>The compliance formula — 'The Israelites did everything the LORD had commanded Moses; so they did' — is the standard closing formula for obedience in Numbers, appearing at key points throughout the book. It signals the completion of a commanded action and the wholeness of Israel's response. The repetition of <em>ken asu</em> (so they did) at the end is characteristic Priestly narrative style.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p>The second major organizational command, given to Moses and Aaron together: the camp arrangement by standards. The involvement of both Moses (civil/military) and Aaron (priestly) in the camp-arrangement command mirrors their joint role in the census — the camp organization is both a military and a liturgical act.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The command to camp 'at a distance around the tent of meeting' establishes the fundamental principle of the camp's layout: radial organization centered on the Tabernacle. The phrase <em>merachok saviv leOhel Mo'ed yachanu</em> (at a distance, around the tent of meeting, shall they camp) creates a spatial hierarchy — the tabernacle at the center, Levites immediately surrounding it (ch.3), and the twelve tribes arranged at a prescribed distance. This concentric arrangement has parallels in Egyptian royal camp layouts: the plan of the Egyptian military camp at the Battle of Kadesh (c. 1274 BCE, relief at Abu Simbel and Luxor) shows the royal tent of Ramesses II at the center of a rectangular camp with troops arranged in four quadrants. The Israelite camp arrangement is structurally analogous: a sacred center with four tribal divisions at the four compass points.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Judah's eastern position, 'toward the sunrise,' places the leading tribe at the most honored compass direction. In ANE cosmology, the east (sunrise) direction was associated with life, divine favor, and the meeting of heaven and earth. Temples and sacred sites were typically oriented toward the east across the ancient world: Egyptian temples face east; the Jerusalem temple's main entrance faced east; Ezekiel's eschatological temple has the glory entering from the east (Ezek 43:2-4). Judah at the sunrise position is a spatial statement of the tribe's destiny as the source of light and kingship.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Judah's enrollment count of 74,600 — the largest of all twelve tribes — places the most numerous fighting force at the head of the march. The eastern quadrant contains three tribes totaling 186,400 men (v9), making it the strongest of the four divisions. The military logic of putting the largest force in the lead (first to encounter enemies) is consistent with ANE military strategy.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Issachar camps adjacent to Judah. The pairing of Issachar and Zebulun with Judah in the eastern division mirrors the geographic proximity of their later territories (Jezreel Valley, lower Galilee) and their sibling relationship as Leah's sons. The eastern division thus consists of three Leah-sons: Judah (fourth), Issachar (ninth), Zebulun (tenth) by birth order.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Issachar: 54,400 — contributing to the eastern division's strength.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Zebulun is the third tribe of the eastern (Judah) division. The consistent pairing of Issachar and Zebulun throughout Numbers (census, camp, march) reflects a geographical and historical association of these tribes that persisted in Israel's memory. Deborah's song (Judg 5:14-18) praises both Zebulun and Issachar for their military valor in the battle against Sisera.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Zebulun: 57,400. The eastern division total will be given in v9.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Eastern division (Judah's standard) total: 186,400 — the largest of the four divisions and the first to march. The explicit note that 'they shall march first' establishes the marching order that is repeated in detail in ch.10:14. Judah's military, demographic, and positional priority is consistent and multidimensional: largest tribe, largest division, sunrise position, first to march.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Reuben's southern position. The south was associated in ANE cosmology with the heat of the midday sun — a position of prominence and power, but secondary to the east. Reuben, technically the firstborn but stripped of his primacy (Gen 49:3-4), is assigned the second-best position rather than the first — a spatial encoding of his ambiguous status. The southern division consists of three sons: Reuben (Leah's first), Simeon (Leah's second), and Gad (Zilpah's first).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Reuben: 46,500.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Simeon camps adjacent to Reuben. The pairing of Reuben and Simeon is consistent with their sibling relationship (Leah's first two sons) and their later geographic proximity in Canaan (Simeon's territory was within Judah's, Josh 19:1-9). The southern division is the smallest of the four, consistent with both Reuben's loss of primacy and Simeon's later population decline.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Simeon: 59,300 — which will decline dramatically by the second census to 22,200.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Gad in the southern division. Gad's placement with Reuben is geographically appropriate since both tribes eventually settle in Transjordan (ch.32). The note that Gad's leader is 'Eliasaph son of Reuel' here (vs. Deuel in 1:14) reflects a minor textual variant in the Masoretic tradition — <em>Re'u'el</em> and <em>De'u'el</em> differ only in the first letter (resh vs. dalet), a common scribal confusion in Hebrew manuscripts.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Gad: 45,650.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Southern division (Reuben's standard) total: 151,450 — the smallest of the four main divisions, marching second. The marching order (Judah first, Reuben second) reflects not just numerical size but tribal precedence: the Leah-firstborn follows the blessing-holder.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The Levites march in the middle, between the first two divisions and the last two. Their central position during the march maintains the spatial relationship of the camp: the tabernacle (and its custodians) are always at the center. Each Levitical clan keeps its assigned position in the march with the tabernacle components in its care (Kohathites with the holy objects, Gershonites and Merarites with the structural components, ch.4). The Levitical buffer zone during the march prevents the holy things from being exposed to the main camp during transit.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Ephraim's western position. The west was associated with sunset and, in Egyptian cosmology, with the realm of the dead (the Valley of the Kings is on the west bank of the Nile). In Israelite thought, the west was simply the direction of the Mediterranean Sea. Ephraim leads the western division — the direction toward Egypt from which Israel came, symbolically appropriate for the Joseph tribes (Ephraim, Manasseh, Benjamin) who represent the Egyptian sojourn period of Israel's history.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Ephraim: 40,500 — the smaller of the two Joseph tribes, consistent with Manasseh's numerical precedence in Numbers though Ephraim has the spiritual precedence from Jacob's blessing (Gen 48:19).</p>",
    "20": "<p>Manasseh camps adjacent to Ephraim. The pairing of the two Joseph half-tribes is natural — they share a father and the Joseph inheritance. In Canaan, their territories are adjacent in the central highlands. The Joseph division (Ephraim, Manasseh, Benjamin) is the western division, making the three sons of Rachel's family the group that faces toward the setting sun.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Manasseh: 32,200.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Benjamin's inclusion in the Ephraim (western) division rather than with his full brother Joseph's sons reflects the military camp organization's pragmatic needs — Benjamin is assigned to the western division alongside the other Rachel descendants. Later, Benjamin's territory and Ephraim's territory are adjacent in Canaan, consistent with this camp pairing.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Benjamin: 35,400.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Western division (Ephraim's standard) total: 108,100 — the smallest division by total enrollment. They march third, after the Levites. The third position is not simply a numerical consequence but an ordering that places the Joseph tribes — associated with the Egyptian years of Israel's slavery — in the central portion of the march, neither at the vanguard nor at the rear.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Dan's northern position. The north in ANE cosmology was associated with the divine mountain (Ugaritic texts describe the divine assembly meeting on the mountain of the north, <em>tsaphon</em>) but also with danger — enemies typically came from the north in the Levant (Jer 1:14: 'out of the north disaster shall be poured'). Dan, the largest tribe in the rear guard, provides the strongest possible protection for the march's vulnerable trailing position.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Dan: 62,700.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Asher adjacent to Dan in the northern division. The northern division consists of Dan (Bilhah's first), Asher (Zilpah's second), and Naphtali (Bilhah's second) — the concubine-sons of Jacob, placed at the rear of the march. This ordering of the divisions by mother-group (Leah's primary sons leading, then Leah's sons in second group, then Rachel's sons, then concubine sons) creates a subtle social-genealogical logic encoded in the military organization.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Asher: 41,500.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Naphtali in the northern division, completing the rear guard. Naphtali's territory in the Galilee region is later associated with the first light of the Messianic age (Isa 9:1-2; Matt 4:15-16), a striking contrast with the tribe's rear-guard position in the wilderness march.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Naphtali: 53,400.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Northern division (Dan's standard) total: 157,600 — marching last, forming the rear guard. The largest division after Judah's is at the rear, ensuring the most powerful protection for the march's most vulnerable position. The strategic logic is sound: both the vanguard (Judah, 186,400) and the rear guard (Dan, 157,600) are the two strongest divisions.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The summary of the entire camp: 603,550 total, organized by ancestral houses. The camp arrangement described in ch.2 is thus the spatial and organizational expression of the census data from ch.1 — the same 603,550 men now have assigned positions, standards, and march order. The two chapters together constitute a complete organizational document: a census registry (ch.1) and a deployment order (ch.2).</p>",
    "33": "<p>The Levitical exemption is restated in the summary: 'The Levites were not enrolled among the Israelites, as the LORD had commanded Moses.' The repetition at the chapter's close reinforces the structural distinction between the organized military camp (the twelve tribes) and the cultic center (the Levites with the tabernacle). The two organizational structures exist simultaneously but operate under different principles.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The compliance formula closes the chapter: 'The Israelites did everything the LORD had commanded Moses: they camped by their standards and they marched each by his clan under his ancestral house.' The double confirmation — camping AND marching — confirms that the organization functions in both stationary and mobile modes. The final words return to the foundational structure of the whole census and camp document: <em>levet avotam</em> (by their ancestral houses). The entire organizational apparatus of Numbers chs.1-2 is built upon the kinship structure of the ancestral household.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'numbers')
    merge_comm(c, CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'numbers', c)
    print('Numbers 1-2 context written.')

